{
    "analysis": "The metric-anomaly detection step was completed and returned metric_thresholds, metric_anomaly_rows, and metric_anomalies. The results show a very large number of anomaly rows (19,379) and many aggregated groups with anomaly_count=31. However, a large subset of these groups have global_p95 == 0 and global_p5 == 0, producing meaningless severity scores and likely representing zero-valued time series or collection/normalization artifacts. To make progress we must exclude those zero-threshold groups and focus on component-KPIs with non-zero thresholds (informative KPIs). The next step is to aggregate anomalies per component excluding zero-threshold KPIs to find which components have the most and most-severe anomalies, and to get earliest anomaly timestamps per component so we can prioritize trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously saved metric_anomalies (which includes per cmdb_id+kpi_name: anomaly_count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, min_value, max_value, global_p5, global_p95, severity_score), do the following and save the result as component_anom_summary:\n1) Filter out all rows where both global_p95 == 0 AND global_p5 == 0 (keep only KPIs with at least one non-zero global threshold).\n2) Group the remaining rows by cmdb_id and compute: num_kpis_with_anomalies (count of distinct kpi_name), total_anomaly_points (sum of anomaly_count), earliest_anomaly (min of earliest_timestamp across KPIs), latest_anomaly (max of latest_timestamp), top_kpi (the kpi_name with the largest anomaly_count for that cmdb_id), top_kpi_count, and max_severity_score (max severity_score for that cmdb_id).\n3) Return a compact table of the top 20 rows sorted by total_anomaly_points desc then max_severity_score desc with columns: cmdb_id, num_kpis_with_anomalies, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly, latest_anomaly, top_kpi, top_kpi_count, max_severity_score.\nAlso store the filtered KPI-level anomalies (nonzero thresholds) in kernel for later trace/log inspection. Keep the returned output bounded to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly detection. Metric anomalies were dominated by zero-valued KPIs (global_p95==0 and global_p5==0) and provided no usable severity signal. Trace analysis produced 969 anomaly rows and highlighted several candidate components and call paths: dockerA2 (trace.self.duration_p95 with 9 anomalies and highest relative severity ~7.77, earliest anomaly around 15:01), MG02↔dockerB2 row_count spikes beginning ~15:06 (severity ~1.43), and IG01↔Tomcat02 row_count spikes beginning ~15:05 (severity ~1.02). From these results we can tentatively hypothesize an early latency spike at dockerA2 around 15:01 that may have preceded the later traffic/row-count bursts at ~15:05–15:06, making dockerA2 a strong candidate for the root cause component. However, to localize the root cause (component and exact occurrence time) we must confirm the temporal ordering and earliest anomalous trace points across top candidates and inspect dockerA2 trace anomaly details. The next atomic step is to extract compact, ordered summaries of trace anomalies by component and the full anomaly rows for dockerA2 within the incident window so we can determine which component first exhibited an anomalous behavior.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously saved trace_anomaly_rows do two things and save outputs in the kernel:\n1) Produce a compact per-component summary: group trace_anomaly_rows by cmdb_id and compute earliest_anomaly (min earliest_timestamp), anomaly_rows_count (sum of anomaly_count across trace_names), max_severity (max severity_score), and top_trace (trace_name with largest anomaly_count). Return up to top 20 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly ascending with columns: cmdb_id, earliest_anomaly, anomaly_rows_count, top_trace, max_severity.\n2) Return the detailed trace_anomaly_rows for cmdb_id == 'dockerA2' (all trace_names) limited to top 20 rows sorted by earliest_timestamp ascending, showing columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, min_value, max_value, global_p5, global_p95, severity_score.\nKeep outputs compact (max 20 rows each)."
}

{
    "analysis": "What has been done: We completed preprocessing and anomaly detection for metrics, traces, and logs. Metrics were largely uninformative because many KPI series are zero-valued or have zero thresholds; logs contained useful signals on Tomcat nodes (GC pauses and row_count bursts) but dockerA2 had no log anomalies. Traces delivered the clearest signal: dockerA2 exhibits the earliest and strongest relative spike in trace.self.duration_p95 (severity ~7.77) starting around 2021-03-24 15:01+08:00, while MG01/MG02/dockerB2/IG01/Tomcat nodes show subsequent row_count and duration anomalies beginning ~15:05–15:06. The dockerA2 metric window shows many container KPIs with either huge constant values or zeros, offering no clear resource-level reason. What needs to be derived next: the exact root-cause occurrence timestamp and whether dockerA2's duration_p95 spike forms a consecutive fault (start time of the fault) large enough to be the root cause. We must extract the detailed anomaly rows for dockerA2.trace.self.duration_p95 (timestamps and values) within the incident window to identify the very first anomalous data point and whether the anomaly persists consecutively (fault identification).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the saved trace anomaly results (or from trace.csv joined with global thresholds if needed), extract the detailed anomaly rows for cmdb_id == 'dockerA2' AND trace_name == 'trace.self.duration_p95' within the incident window 2021-03-24 15:00 to 15:30 (UTC+8). Return up to 50 rows sorted by timestamp ascending and show these columns: timestamp, value, global_p5, global_p95, and severity_score (e.g., value/global_p95 when global_p95>0). Also store the returned table in the kernel variable dockerA2_self_p95_anom for subsequent steps." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We extracted detailed anomalies for dockerA2.trace.self.duration_p95 within the incident window. Findings: a pronounced p95 latency spike at 2021-03-24 15:01:00+08:00 with value=0.1298s and severity≈7.77 (value >> global P95), a smaller exceedance at 15:08 (value=0.0204s, severity≈1.22), and otherwise low values near the global P5. This establishes dockerA2 experienced an early, significant latency fault at 15:01+08:00. Trace analysis across the system shows downstream row_count and duration anomalies on MG and Tomcat components beginning ~15:05–15:06, consistent with propagation from an upstream service slowdown. Logs contained no dockerA2 anomalies; Tomcat nodes show GC and row-count increases later. Metrics for dockerA2 exist but many series are zero-valued or contain very large constants; we have an aggregate table of dockerA2 KPIs but the KPI names were truncated in output so their meaning is unclear. At this point dockerA2 is the strongest root-cause candidate by temporal precedence and trace severity, but the underlying reason (CPU/memory/GC/network/disk) is not yet confirmed because dockerA2 logs did not show helpful anomalies and its metric KPIs need clearer inspection (full KPI names and values) to interpret resource signals.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Show the dockerA2 metric aggregate (dockerA2_metric_aggr) with full kpi_name strings (no truncation). Return the top 20 kpi groups sorted by max_value descending with columns: kpi_name, count, min_value, max_value, mean_value. This will help interpret which resource KPIs have non-zero or very large values for dockerA2 so we can infer the underlying reason (CPU, memory, network, disk, or container-level issue). Keep output bounded to 20 rows."
}

